1. Single (Simple) Inheritance: Involves exactly one Super Class and one Sub Class extending it 
05:48
Opens in a new window.

2. Multilevel Inheritance: Involves a chain of classes. For example, a Super Class is extended by Sub Class 1, which is then extended by Sub Class 2. In this structure, Sub Class 2 can access features from both Sub Class 1 and the original Super Class 
06:18
Opens in a new window.

3. Multiple Inheritance (Not Supported with Classes): This involves a single Sub Class trying to extend multiple Super Classes at the same time. Java does not support this via classes because if both superclasses have a method with the same name, it creates an ambiguity error for the sub-class. However, multiple inheritance is supported in Java using Interfaces 
07:26
Opens in a new window.

4. Hierarchical Inheritance: Involves a single Super Class that is directly extended by multiple different Sub Classes 
08:07
Opens in a new window.

Difference from Multilevel: In hierarchical inheritance, all sub-classes directly communicate with the main parent class, rather than forming a sequential chain